  "market_context": "Both GC (Gold Futures) and XAUGBP trade up into their respective range highs on the 1-hour chart without producing an SMT divergence between them, setting up a potential reversal scenario within the gold triad correlation.",
  "key_observation": "Even though no SMT formed at the range high between GC and XAUGBP, a PSP (precision swing point) printed where GC closed bearish while XAUGBP closed bullish on the same candle, confirming the reversal from the range high.",
  "analysis_steps": [
    "Step 1: Pull up the gold triad using the Forex.com feed, placing GC on the left and XAUGBP on the right, both on the 1-hour timeframe.",
    "Step 2: Observe that price trades into the range high on both assets without producing an SMT divergence.",
    "Step 3: Identify the PSP at the range high where the two correlated assets close in opposite directions, confirming the reversal.",
    "Step 4: Move to the 4-hour timeframe to identify the first-stage SMT formed between a gap/level on the higher timeframe.",
    "Step 5: Drop down to the 30-minute timeframe to locate the second-stage SMT confirming the higher timeframe SMT.",
    "Step 6: With the two-stage SMT sequence confirmed, target the opposing side of the range (the external 4-hour range) as the draw on liquidity.",
    "Step 7: Watch price trade perfectly into the opposing range side and look for continuation PSPs (e.g., a 5:30 candle closing bearish on GC and bullish on XAUGBP) to continue the move."
  ],
  "outcome": "Price traded perfectly from the range high down into the opposing side of the 4-hour range, with continuation PSPs forming along the way.",
  "lessons": "When two correlated assets reach a key level without printing an SMT, a PSP (opposite closes on the same candle) can still confirm the reversal. Combining a two-stage SMT sequence across HTF and LTF strengthens the reversal thesis and targets the opposing range side.",
